Health Expenditures in the United States

Expendature Causes Over Time


The first plot shows the change in spending over the course of this study on the 5 broad causes that encompass all spending. As shown, spending on the Non-communicable diseases cause is much higher and increasing at a much faster rate than all of the other top changers. I did some research on the WHO website (http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs355/en/) and found that this category might include spending on respiratory diseases, heart disease, cancers, as well as many other diseases that are expensive to treat and fairly common. I have graphed all other categories separately to get a better understanding of how they individually increase.

Looking at the other data sets, they all have similar yearly rates of increase, even when expenditure values are adjusted for inflation. This means that overall medical expenditures are increasing across a wide variety of categories. All categories also seemed to stabilize in the 2010s, which may have been due to healthcare regulation at a federal level by president Obama. I wanted to explore what caused this so I looked at a break down of what is increasing for the broad category of Non Communicable diseases.

Increase in Category Expenses Over Time


In this bar graph, each health care function is shown as a different color in the stack. This allows for us to compare which parts of health care costs rose in each year. I expected that one type of cost would be the culprit of most of the increase, however that was not the case. Each year showed a pretty small and uniform increase for each category of expense, which added up over time to make a big difference in total expense. To further explore categorical increases, I looked at pharmacy expenses over time, because this is an issue that gets a lot of attention in the media with stories about increased drug prices.

Increase in Pharmacy Expenses Over Time


Pharmacy costs increased dramatically from the late 90s through around 2008, when they began to stabilize and then taper off. This time frame aligns with when the Obama administrations health care legislation started to roll out, which may have attributed to a lowering in drug prices. State legislation also helped halt drug manufacturers price increases.Pharmacy

Health Expenditure by Sex and Age Group


Above is a stacked bar chart comparing the total health expenditures of men and women across the various age groups of the study. Overall, health expenditures increase as the cohort ages, and more tends to be spent on women as they age. This may be because women have a higher life expectancy, and there will therefore be more of them incurring healthcare costs compared to men later in life. Because health expenditures are so big towards the end of ones life, I looked in to the main causes of expenditure, and compared them across sex to see what some of the most costly issues are.

The top causes of health expense for the elderly were uniform across sex, which gives me confidence that the higher proportion of expense due to females is due to their longer life expectancy, and not another cause that adds more cost. I also found it interesting that more money is spent on women with dementia, and wonder if there is a higher prevalence of dementia among women. Heart disease, often atrributed to smoking, poor diet, and alchohol use was more common amoung elderly men.

Varience in Cancer Expenditures


The graph above shows the difference in health care expenditures by type across different Cancers. According to the Department of Health (https://www.cancer.gov/types/common-cancers), the top listed cancers are some of the most prevalent cancers in the United States. For these most prevalent cancers, the majority of spending seems to be on outpatient (AM) care. This is especially true for breast cancer and skin cancer. Breast cancer also stood out as having very high Pharmacy expenses compared to the rest of the cancers. After some brief research, I found that drugs used for breast cancer have been criticized for price gauging by their makers (http://www.reuters.com/article/us-pfizer-britain-cancer-idUSKBN15I00B).
